[2]
Date: 17 Jun 2011
Source: Tanjug [edited]
http://www.emg.rs/en/news/serbia/158094.html


Anthrax in Serbia -- situation in infected zones under control
--------------------------------------------------------------
The situation in 2 villages in Vojvodina that have been declared
anthrax-infected zones is under control and there is minimum
possibility for the spread of the disease, Maja Andrijasevic of the
Ministry of Agriculture Veterinary Directorate said Friday [17 Jun
2011].

"Citizens can feel absolutely positive that everything they eat and
drink is safe," Andrijasevic said in connection with the current
situation in the villages of Bocar and Novo Milosevo that have been
declared anthrax-infected zones. Andrijasevic said that from the
moment the disease had been diagnosed, the relevant veterinary
service, veterinary institute and the competent veterinary inspection
were out there in the field and implementing prescribed measures. The
implementation of control measures is still under way, she added.

The disease is usually related to veterinarians, as they are more
likely to get into contact with an infected animal, while the rest of
the population is safe and there is minimum possibility for the spread
of the disease, Andrijasevic said for the Radio and Television of
Serbia (RTS). [I wish this statement were true but unfortunately we
have stupid livestock owners. - Mod.MHJ]

As regards the current ban on eating milk and meat from the animals
in the 2 villages, she said that vaccination of the animals was
underway, during which time cattle must not be slaughtered for meat or
their milk used for human consumption. Andrijasevic said that the
vaccination would be carried out in the 2 villages over the following
20 years, enough to protect the population and animals there from
infection.

Commenting on the data that anthrax appeared in the region already in
mid-1970's, she said anthrax bacteria spores stayed dormant in the
soil for 30 to 60 years and could become active under conditions such
as heavy rainfall, flooding or drought. She recalled that cases of
anthrax infections had been registered in Tutin, southern Serbia, in
2007, and that the necessary actions were being taken there as well.

--
Communicated by:
